      • caughtSpeeding

        public int caughtSpeeding(int speed,
                          boolean isBirthday)
        You are driving a little too fast, and a police officer stops you. Write code to compute the result, encoded as an int value: 0=no ticket, 1=small ticket, 2=big ticket. If speed is 60 or less, the result is 0. If speed is between 61 and 80 inclusive, the result is 1. If speed is 81 or more, the result is 2. Unless it is your birthday -- on that day, your speed can be 5 higher in all cases. caughtSpeeding(60, false) → 0 caughtSpeeding(65, false) → 1 caughtSpeeding(65, true) → 0
        Parameters:
        speed - int, it defines the speed
        isBirthday - boolean, it us true if the current day is birthday
        Returns:
        int, it could be 0, 1 or 2. If speed is between 61 and 80 inclusive, the result is 1. If speed is 81 or more, the result is 2. Unless it is your birthday -- on that day, your speed can be 5 higher in all cases.

      • teaParty

        public int teaParty(int tea,
                    int candy)
        We are having a party with amounts of tea and candy. Return the int outcome of the party encoded as 0=bad, 1=good, or 2=great. A party is good (1) if both tea and candy are at least 5. However, if either tea or candy is at least double the amount of the other one, the party is great (2). However, in all cases, if either tea or candy is less than 5, the party is always bad (0). teaParty(6, 8) → 1 teaParty(3, 8) → 0 teaParty(20, 6) → 2
        Parameters:
        tea - int, defines how many teas are there
        candy - int, defines how many candies are there
        Returns:
        int, it could be 0=bad, 1=good, or 2=great (1:if both tea and candy are at least 5 or 2:if either tea or candy is at least double the amount of the other one or 3: in all cases, if either tea or candy is less than 5 or 0: every other hand)

Otherwise the result is 0. blueTicket(9, 1, 0) → 10 blueTicket(9, 2, 0) → 0 blueTicket(6, 1, 4) → 10
        Parameters:

      • alarmClock

        public java.lang.String alarmClock(int day,
                                   boolean vacation)
        Given a day of the week encoded as 0=Sun, 1=Mon, 2=Tue, ...6=Sat, and a boolean indicating if we are on vacation, return a string of the form "7:00" indicating when the alarm clock should ring. Weekdays, the alarm should be "7:00" and on the weekend it should be "10:00". Unless we are on vacation -- then on weekdays it should be "10:00" and weekends it should be "off". alarmClock(1, false) → "7:00" alarmClock(5, false) → "7:00" alarmClock(0, false) → "10:00"
        Parameters:
        day - int, eg: 0=Sun, 1=Mon, 2=Tue, ...6=Sat
        vacation - boolean, its true if the current day is vacation
        Returns:
        string, its if "7:00" indicating when the alarm clock should ring. Weekdays, the alarm should be "7:00" and on the weekend it should be "10:00". Unless we are on vacation -- then on weekdays it should be "10:00" and weekends it should be "off"

        Parameters:
        n - int
        Returns:
        string, its form of the number followed by "!". So the int 6 yields "6!". Except if the number is divisible by 3 use "Fizz" instead of the number, and if the number is divisible by 5 use "Buzz", and if divisible by both 3 and 5, use "FizzBuzz".

        Parameters:
        a - int, non-negative number
        b - int, non-negative number
        Returns:
